qas.question: What happens in a chennel transupport system?

answers.text: several proteins form a contiguous channel traversing the inner and outer membranes of the bacteria

qas.question: What three protien subunites are in the chennel transupport system?

answers.text: the ABC protein, membrane fusion protein (MFP), and outer membrane protein (OMP)[specify]

qas.question: What does this secretion system transport?

answers.text: various molecules, from ions, drugs, to proteins of various sizes

context: In a channel transupport system, <a0_0>several proteins form a contiguous channel traversing the inner and outer membranes of the bacteria<a0_0/>. It is a simple system, which consists of only three protein subunits: <a1_0>the ABC protein, membrane fusion protein (MFP), and outer membrane protein (OMP)[specify]<a1_0/>. This secretion system transports <a2_0>various molecules, from ions, drugs, to proteins of various sizes<a2_0/> (20 - 900 kDa). The molecules secreted vary in size from the small Escherichia coli peptide colicin V, (10 kDa) to the Pseudomonas fluorescens cell adhesion protein LapA of 900 kDa.
